The Giralda, now the bell tower of Sevilla's large and magnificent gothic cathedral, has a long and strange history. First built as a minaret by the Almohad caliphs in the twelfth century, at the end of the golden age of Al-Andalus, it was partially reshaped and heightened up to 104 metres in the Christian age. Together with the Patio de los naranjos (Garden of the Orange Trees), a peaceful and geometrically arranged courtyard accessible from the side of the cathedral, the Giralda stands as the only witness of what once was one of the greatest and richest mosques of Andalusia. Visiting Sevilla's cathedral thus becomes a way of reflecting on the many faces of history while enjoying some fresh air and the pungent smell of oranges.

Sevilla's Alcázares Reales are one of the most refined examples of mudéjar architecture, a style which flourished in the early fourteenth century and saw Christian buildings flirt with shapes, motives and designs that were clearly reminiscent of Islamic art (and that were, in fact, largely commissioned to Arab craftsmen). It is all too easy to let the eyes wander around and get lost inside the many different and intricate patterns on the walls and arches. This timeless architectural beauty is still partly used as a royal residence and has been listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
